Fix for issue #1991 regarding setting intervening models to None.

This particular issue involves joining 3 models together in a chain,
where the outer two models are empty. Previously peewee would make the
middle model an empty model instance (since a link might be needed from
the source model to the outermost model). But since both were empty, it
is more correct to make the intervening model a NULL value on the
foreign-key field rather than an empty instance.

Implement text-based decimal field for Sqlite.

Sqlite uses double-precision floats to store decimal values, which can
result in truncation or other quirks when using particular values. This
patch adds a playhouse.sqlite_ext.TDecimalField subclass which stores
the value in a text-affinity column, which preserves the original value.
The caveat is that attempting to do math in the database will result in
conversion/possible truncation.

Some operating systems don't have sqlite3 module within python3.
without this commit, they will get unclear error message like this:

```
File "/usr/local/lib/python3.4/site-packages/peewee.py", line 3371, in
connect
    **self.connect_kwargs)
  File "/usr/local/lib/python3.4/site-packages/peewee.py", line 3609, in
_connect
    conn = sqlite3.connect(database, **kwargs)
AttributeError: 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'connect'
```

Those users who encounter this ImproperlyConfiguredError
may have to install sqlite dependencies and recompile their python3

Test parsing complex expression in update query

I decided to "pass through" the parse logic if the value is not a
special query component.  Another option would have been to pass in
``conv=field`` when parsing the ``expr`` and rely on the ``parse_expr``
method to do the appropriate conversion.  THis would also allow us to
remove the list comprehension, since ``parse_expr`` is responsible for
doing the same.

The reason I chose not to go this route is because of the way that
parse_expr handles lists/tuples.  Typically a list or tuple will be used
to express a list of values for an "IN" clause in a query.  The current
logic in ``parse_expr`` is designed to handle this case, generating the
appropriate number of interpolation characters, etc.

Things get weird when we assign a list to a field and rely on the
field's db_value method to fix it before sending to the DB.

It comes down to not knowing whether to call db_value() before parsing
or call it after.  We can't call it before in all cases because the expr
may be an expression or something that needs to be parsed first.

Holy shit. It doesn't look like much but this one simple change will now
allow cursors to be gc'd and the database (at least under sqlite) to be
closed properly.  I believe that when I was assigning to _iter_fn it
created a loop that prevented the garbage collector from collecting
QueryResultWrapper instances, which in turn prevented cursors from being
collected, since QRW refers to a cursor. This was causing an
"OperationalError" when closing the connection, reporting unfinalised
statements. Googling it looked like this was caused when cursors
were left around. I threw all cursors and queries into a weakref
dictionary and saw what was still there when I went to close. The
cursors were all being referred to by QRW instances.  I went to see what
was holding onto the QRW instances and it was the "_iter_fn".
